slope of gamma = 1 (Sigma \ensuremath{\propto} r-gamma). Inside 20
AU, the gas surface density drops by a factor of at least 110. The drops
are measured relative to the extrapolation to small radii of the surface
density law at radii \ensuremath{>}60 AU. The inner radius of the gas disk at 20
AU can be constrained to better than \ensuremath{\pm}5 AU. Conclusions:
The derived gas surface density profile points to the clearing of the
cavity by one or more massive planets/companions rather than just
photoevaporation or grain-growth.

